Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: China Loosens Up on Corporate Cash
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: China Loosens Up on Corporate Cash

PARAGRAPH.#text: Moving cash in and out of China is getting easier – for some companies. A pilot program launched late last year allows banks to set up so-called sweep accounts in China, which let companies pool extra cash from accounts both there and elsewhere into a single account. The money can then be redistributed to other company accounts in the form of short-term intercompany loans, and invested more broadly, CFOJ's Vipal Monga writes in today's Marketplace section.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: China Loosens Up on Corporate Cash

Headlines.SeoHeadline: China Eases Its Grip on Cash
Headlines.Author: Vipal Monga
Headlines.Headline: China Eases Its Grip on Cash

PARAGRAPH.#text: China is joining the modern era of corporate cash management—in its own measured way. Late last year, China quietly introduced a pilot program that allows a handful of global companies to move funds in and out of the country in short-term transactions, and streamlines some cross-border payments. Those concessions could save companies with a large presence in China millions of dollars a year, bankers say, and could bolster the country's efforts to turn Beijing and Shanghai into major international financial centers.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: China Eases Its Grip on Cash

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: What Happened to the Recovery?
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: What Happened to the Recovery?

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Recovery reality check. After a winter of upside surprises, we're suddenly seeing a lot of worrying economic numbers. Layoffs are on the upswing, home sales are slumping and even manufacturing is starting to look shaky, the WSJ says on A1. The slowdown "in part reflects an unusually warm winter, which pulled forward economic activity, making January and February seem artificially good and perhaps making recent weeks look worse than they truly were," the NYT says. We're still seeing light at the end of the tunnel – it's just that we're stuck in a really long tunnel.
THE DAY AHEAD:
GE just reported a 12% drop in net profit – but revenue came a little better than expected, up 4% excluding NBCUniversal. A little later this morning we'll hear from McDonald's, Honeywell and Kimberly Clark. Europe tops the agenda at the annual IMF/World Bank Spring meeting in D.C. where IMF Chief Christine Lagarde is looking to boost the fund's lending capacity.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways
Headlines.Author: David Hall
Headlines.Headline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Businesses balk at tax proposals. We're not hearing much praise from the business community for President Obama's tax proposals in the State of the Union address. Tom Deas, treasurer of fertilizer maker FMC Corp., told us the president's call for a minimum tax on overseas profits could make American multinationals less competitive. "If it's demonstrably better for a U.S. company that makes products overseas to place factories near their customers," it shouldn't be penalized for making that business decision, he said. Snap-On CEO Nicholas Pinchuk told the Journal's John Bussey that he liked the proposal to ease the tax burden for domestic manufacturers, but Obama "seemed to mention several new regulations even as he spoke of reduction." And the former CFO of a large consumer products company suggested that rather than penalizing companies for offshoring jobs, the government should use tax policy to incentivize job creation in the U.S. "Our government must recognize we live in a world economy, not a U.S. economy," he said.
That's a message Corporate America is going to have to make forcefully next month when the Treasury Department outlines corporate-tax code changes. The WSJ says the administration understands the "political challenges of crafting tax changes. But part of their strategy is to begin negotiations with Republicans and business groups now so changes might be added at the end of the year when Congress decides how to address the expiring Bush-era tax cuts."

Headlines.BodyHeadline: The Morning Ledger: Low Rates Cut Two Ways

PARAGRAPH.#text: (This article was originally published Monday.) NEW YORK (Dow Jones)--The Oakmark Global Fund OAKGX has cut its holdings of companies based in places like China and India to zero, while many investors who traditionally focused on domestic stocks are expanding into emerging markets. Nearly 20% of the fund's position is based in Japan, even as the country's Nikkei 225 index has suffered a 6.8% drop this year. "These aren't intentional" regional allocations, said Clyde McGregor, who co-manages the $2.2 billion fund of 40 stocks with Rob Taylor.

Headlines.Author: Shawn Langlois
Headlines.Headline: Snap-on Profit Jumps 45% On Overseas Demand

#text: By Shawn Langlois SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones) -- Snap-on Inc. on Tuesday reported a 45% improvement in first-quarter profit thanks to increased industrial demand for the company's tools as well as strong growth in sales to overseas customers. Still, Snap-on

shares, which have already rallied more than 10% this year, succumbed to the broader market selling to close down 3.9% at $53.12. The Kenosha, Wis., developer of hand and power tools posted a profit of $56.6 million, or 97 cents a share, up from $39 million, or 66 cents a share, a year earlier.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Snap-on Profit Jumps 45% On Overseas Demand

Headlines.Author: Jonathan Burton
Headlines.Headline: LIFE SAVINGS: Five Mutual Funds To Keep Your Kid In Prep School

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Jonathan Burton SAN FRANCISCO (Dow Jones) -- Getting into a private high school is competitive. Paying for it is even tougher. Parents save for years to put a child through college, and both time and financial incentives are on their side. Funding options for private college preparatory school, however, don't make the same grade. Families basically are on their own -- there's no high-school equivalent of tax-friendly 529 college savings plans, and the Coverdell Education Savings Account is saddled with strict income and investment limits.

Headlines.Author: Barbara C. Costanza
Headlines.Headline: Snap-On, Level 3 provide caution on outlooks
Headlines.BodyHeadline: Snap-On, Level 3 provide caution on outlooks

#text: Temporary professional staffing services company On Assignment

advised investors that its second-quarter earnings would be in the range of 18 cents to 19 cents a share, compared with 20 cents in the year-ago period. Analysts polled by First Call had been expecting a profit of 22 cents a share. Revenue will be flat with the year-ago total of $47.8 million. For the year, the company expects earnings of 82 cents to 85 cents a share, with revenue of about $195 million. Previously, the company expected earnings of 93 cents to 96 cents a share, on revenue of about $220 million to $225 million. The company also announced a significantly expanded share repurchase authorization. Shares closed down 45 cents to $21.75.
